    {
      "title": "The Craftsman, Sharecropper, Thief, and Related Classes: Chazakah and Testifying Rights",
      "display_title": "Craftsman & Thief Cases",
      "timestamp": "10:57",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rebbi Yochanan's teaching on the craftsman and sharecropper: they have no chazakah, but their children do",
          "display_title": "Uman & Aris Rule",
          "timestamp": "10:57"
        },
        {
          "title": "The thief and son of thief have no chazakah; grandson of thief has chazakah",
          "display_title": "Gazlan Hierarchy",
          "timestamp": "13:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's question: what does Rebbi Yochanan mean? Do they come with their father's claim or not?",
          "display_title": "Gemara's Inquiry",
          "timestamp": "14:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The key distinction: witnesses testifying that the original owner admitted to the father",
          "display_title": "Witness Admission",
          "timestamp": "16:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Why even with admission, a gazlan's grandson might not have chazakah: coerced admission",
          "display_title": "Coerced Admission",
          "timestamp": "17:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rebbi Yochanan vs Rav Chisda: is the gazlan disqualified only for this field or for all fields?",
          "display_title": "RY vs RC Dispute",
          "timestamp": "19:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "The opinion that even a gazlan can be believed if he does teshuvah",
          "display_title": "Gazlan Teshuvah",
          "timestamp": "20:40"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Additional Cases of Chazakah Qualification: Craftsman Who Quit, Sharecropper Who Quit, and Independent Children",
      "display_title": "Chazakah Qualifications",
      "timestamp": "23:58",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Craftsman who quits his profession can create chazakah; sharecropper who quits can create chazakah",
          "display_title": "Quit Profession Rule",
          "timestamp": "23:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Adult child who no longer lives at home is treated as independent for chazakah purposes",
          "display_title": "Adult Child Rule",
          "timestamp": "24:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Divorced woman has independent chazakah rights; explanation of why this is not obvious",
          "display_title": "Divorced Woman",
          "timestamp": "24:47"
        },
        {
          "title": "Case of uncertain divorce (safek m'gureshah): woman may have chazakah despite husband's continued support obligations",
          "display_title": "Safek Divorce",
          "timestamp": "26:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Proof is sufficient: if a person brings witnesses or a document, chazakah can be established for various categories",
          "display_title": "Proof Suffices",
          "timestamp": "27:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Exception: gazlan's proof is not believed because witnesses are assumed to be coerced",
          "display_title": "Gazlan Proof Rejected",
          "timestamp": "28:16"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Sikrikon Case: Stolen Property Sold and Resold, and the Nature of Coerced Sales",
      "display_title": "Stolen Property Sale",
      "timestamp": "29:52",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The case: sikrikon steals from Reuven, sells to Shimon; Shimon then buys again from Reuven",
          "display_title": "Sikrikon Scenario",
          "timestamp": "29:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav's opinion: sale through chazakah is invalid; sale by shtar is valid",
          "display_title": "Rav's Position",
          "timestamp": "31:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shmuel's stringent opinion: even sale by shtar is invalid unless achrayut nechasim is included",
          "display_title": "Shmuel's Position",
          "timestamp": "32:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "Achrayut nechasim explained: removing lien obligations shows genuine intent to sell",
          "display_title": "Achrayut Explained",
          "timestamp": "35:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Bibi clarifies: the distinction applies to land (karka) but not to money (maos)",
          "display_title": "Rav Bibi Clarification",
          "timestamp": "38:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Witness testimony regarding admission of amounts: must specify the amount, not just general admission",
          "display_title": "Witness Specificity",
          "timestamp": "39:12"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Nature of Coercion and the Validity of Coerced Sales",
      "display_title": "Coerced Sales",
      "timestamp": "41:43",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Kahana: a gazlan coerces the original owner into admitting by threatening to give it to another thief",
          "display_title": "Gazlan Coercion",
          "timestamp": "41:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Huna: even a sale made under threat (hung up, forced) is valid",
          "display_title": "Threatened Sale Valid",
          "timestamp": "42:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The reasoning: a person would never sell anything without some form of external pressure (ones)",
          "display_title": "Ones Reasoning",
          "timestamp": "42:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Potential objection: is there a distinction between life-threatening ones and financial pressure?",
          "display_title": "Types of Ones",
          "timestamp": "44:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "The baraita on forced korban: Beis Din can force until person says 'I want to'",
          "display_title": "Forced Korban",
          "timestamp": "44:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Application to gittin: Beis Din can force husband to give get until he agrees",
          "display_title": "Forced Get",
          "timestamp": "45:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "Fundamental principle: even under force, if person agrees, it is valid",
          "display_title": "Force & Agreement",
          "timestamp": "46:26"
        }
      ]
